column1: 185191;instagram;2019-01-19 13:50:36;FALSE;"i‚Äôm pulling a britney and shaving my head....for charity.
i am raising money for two charity's that do work in two areas that sit close to my heart.
beyond blue who do amazing work raising awareness for mental health and provide a safe place for those suffering as well as suicide prevention.
the full stop foundation who work raising awareness for sexual and domestic violence and also provide a safe place for survivors to get help and advice.
time and place of head shave tbc

it's been 11 years since britney spears had her very public break down and shaved her head.  at that time mental illness was not widely known about and it was very much a taboo.  she was ridiculed and mocked nationally.  come forward those years and nearly every body knows about mental illness and how so many people can suffer from it.  wether it's for a little while or something you end up living with
column2: we can now all at least understand what it is and how it effects those we love.

column1: i myself suffer on and off with depression and it is something i have had to come to terms with and live with
column2: which has been extremely hard and still a work in progress. my cousin took his life at age 19 a mere few years ago due to depression
column3: it was a massive shock to all the family as he had everything in life ahead of him.  so this i do for him
column4: my tribute to help even a little with those suffering and feeling like there is only one way out.

column1: another cause that is close to my heart is the awareness of sexual and domestic abuse.  i know all too many people
column3: who have been effected by these subjects and it absolutely pains me that there is still very little justice for those survivors.  more education in schools
column5: universitys and work placements is needed about consent and what is and isn't appropriate behaviour.  social awareness is still a work in progress
column6: but we have come such a long way in reconising just how many women and men have been effected by this ""taboo""  subject
column7: especially through the #metoo movement which was so empowering to many.  #charity #headshave #baldforacause #shavetosave";;en;#metoo

column1: 185205;instagram;2019-01-19 13:54:08;FALSE;"if you want to be successful you are going to need confidence!

column2: confidence is the energy that helps us feel aligned with what we desire. and it helps us attract what we want too.

column1: i remember when i first began my healing journey
column2: as much as i wanted that thriving business and fame... i wasn't confident of my skills or my worth and so it was impossible for me to succeed.
i tried to find it everywhere.

column1: i asked my teacher for it...he said ""find it within""
i asked my biz coach...she said ""you've got to just do it""
i asked my pr coach...she said ""go get some press""
i asked my friends... they said ""we love you""
and so round and round i went in search of what i wanted but one thing was always missing-- and that was my confidence. i didn't believe i was talented. i didn't know in my bones that i was worthy.
and so it was no surprise that i was struggling.
fast forward to today and i am full of confidence. and not in an egocentric
column2: head up my arse type of way.

column1: my confidence stems from the knowledge that i know who i am and what i have accomplished and that helps me stay in alignment with what i am doing and that feels so good!
so if you're like me and you're still looking for the ""confidence fix"" as i call it
with yourself. that's right. confidence starts with you.
so start to spend time every single day with yourself.
do look at yourself in the mirror.
do tell yourself ""i love you"" every single day.
do make a list of all your accomplishments.
do toot your own horn every now and then.
do dance around and celebrate your wins.
do remind yourself why you are here and celebrate it.

do any of these or all of them and you will begin to feel it growing inside you like a tiny seed. self confidence & self worth will sprout up inside you and soon you will be strong like the tallest oak tree.
yes plant your seeds and you will grow anything you wish. but it all starts with confidence.

2. learn your triggers- every pain has a trigger ;for me i can‚Äôt watch certain shows because they are triggers and i don‚Äôt want to self-inflict painful memories

5. don‚Äôt inflict your pain on someone else- just because you haven‚Äôt healed doesn‚Äôt mean the next person deserves to suffer.
6. you are no longer a victim you are a victor. you survived what was meant to break you.

-you realized you didn‚Äôt have to carry the weight of your past any longer?
-you didn‚Äôt have to continue doing the same things just because they were ‚Äúnormal‚Äù
-you didn‚Äôt need to keep letting the fear gremlins or negative self-talk rule your life
-you didn‚Äôt have to stay stuck in the same struggling relationships or friendships
-you could retrain your mind to combat anxiety
-you could restructure all your beliefs so that everything from the past was just a lesson you learned from instead of a setback that made you feel unworthy
-and you could live in a state of being where you were so amped up and in love with yourself that you didn‚Äôt let negativity from others bring you down

your dream life is possible. your happiness
and i hold a key to all of it. but i don‚Äôt want to keep it to myself. üóù
i want everyone to know this truth and to come to love themselves fully and live out their dream lives.üïä .
we were put here to make the most out of our human experience

column1: 185424;instagram;2019-01-19 16:58:58;FALSE;10 year challenge. i may lose some followers because of this. i may make you feel uncomfortable with this post but this is 100% for me. when i was a child i was both sexually and psychologically abused. growing up baptist everything was swept under the rug. the picture on left was when i was 15. at the time i was addicted to pain killers and attempted to take my own life twice. but everything was hidden behind my smile. i was known as the funny one. i was known as the clean cut good boy. since then my addiction has gone away. i still manage to smile every once in a while. i still dress up. i'm not as clean  cut . i still feel pain. but i've picked myself up by the bootstraps. there have been so many people in my life but only a handful who have managed to help me through everything. i love you all and i can really use your prayers today. the past few weeks have been extremely painful and rocky. i love you all. but i especially love @nomi_the_nomad for being the one who has pulled me through my darkest of days. you are the light of my life. #metoo #keepfighting #keepgoing #love;;en;#metoo

column1: 185720;instagram;2019-01-19 20:27:56;FALSE;"some of you know my story. some of you do not.
today i proclaimed my pain and i have never been so loved by so many strangers. hugs. solidarity. apologies. tears.
june 6th 2015 i went to prom and that night my life was changed forever. no one should ever have to experience sexual assault but i did.
june 2016 i went to the police and my case was thrown out for lack of evidence.
june 2017 i ran my first triathlon and reclaimed my body for my own.
june 2018 i completed my first half-ironman and pushed my body to its limits.
today i walked with my head held high and my sister standing next to me. i am fortunate enough to be a survivor. i will continue to fight for my sister
column3: my grandmas... and the women that suffer so greatly in this corrupt world.

(their statement is linked in the comments.) feminists at macewan support all women & believe survivors. we want to acknowledge that in many cases the experiences of survivors of colour are pushed aside and are not held to the same value as those of white survivors.
we encourage our fellow feminists and activists to be critical & vocal of the actions of march on edmonton.

column1: why do we march? to protest the deportation of refugees and undocumented people. for low-income immigrant families choosing between food stamps and a green card. for the disability community experiencing cuts to healthcare. for sex workers facing sesta/fosta. for families separated by the muslim ban

column4: and so many more reasons. we march for all of us.

column1: 185871;instagram;2019-01-19 22:12:28;FALSE;"* w o m e n ' s  m a r c h *

column3: i marched alone and made friends along the way. last year
column4: i marched in sisterhood and solidarity for all those that came forward and said #metoo - i marched to show my sisters i believed them and i was in awe of their strength.

column2: i marched for more personal reasons and i marched with my favorite @heyhanrae by my side.

column1: this year i marched against the patriarchy that is still so rampant in muslim communities - i marched because patriarchy has no place in islam and it has no place in our communities. to believe that man is superior and should oppress women is to go against islam - a faith that has exalted women. the prophet (pbuh) celebrated daughters and spoke out against female infanticide and in his last sermon reminded us that the best of you are those that are best to their wives and also exalted mothers and taught us that paradise lies at the feet of a mother. when our faith celebrates and values women
column2: who is man to say they are superior?

column1: i also marched against the stereotypes of the hijab that i wear. my hijab does not oppress me - it liberates me
column2: it empowers me and it gives me courage. it is my choice to wear it and it is a reminder to me that again my faith commands me to stand up against injustices
column3: speak up for those oppressed and to always be thinking of those less fortunate than me.

column1: 185931;instagram;2019-01-19 22:59:59;FALSE;"stumbled on this quote from #sheilaheti and it resonated. the sense of myself as a mother is playing out everywhere right now (including in my own response to tomorrow's #twft52 prompt). ‚úíüñ§
motherhood is a kaleidoscope of shifting emotions
column2: a dance of connection and awareness. i found myself sorting through hundreds of old photos of my son (the youngest in my blended brood of five
column3: and the only one with my genes
column4: as evidenced by literally every picture of my wonderful crew). but a number of the older pics also included the person who engaged in the abusive behaviors at the center of my story
column5: as well as the one should have protected me. i still can't reconcile it all. i know that it played a role in my extreme reluctance to become a parent; how could i possibly have believed i was equipped?

column1: choosing motherhood may have been the first true act of faith of my life; choosing it again as a stepmother was another. would i fail them? have i? (i'm sure the answer is yes
column2: many times.) there isn't any one right way to become - or to be
column5: to not want to be - a mother
column6: a parent. i never expected to want it
column8: it still took years to feel like something i could claim as identity
column9: not just because i rebelled against the demographic stereotypes (jeans
column12: all intended as sexless and self-less)
column13: but because of the not-good-enoughs. motherhood for me rarely resembles any depiction i've ever seen

column3: in every role i occupy in this life. most certainly
column4: it's here in this work. i hope that's a good thing. i really do.
